icians and their contemporaries made sense of extraordinary musical and physical abilities. This is a history told as much from scientific and medical writings as traditionally musicological ones. Davies describes competing notions of vocal and pianistic health, contrasts techniques of training, and explores the ways in which music acts in the cultivation of bodies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusicxPerformancexHistory. 0aMusicy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  acastrato.  acelebrity pianists.  afranz liszt.  afrederic francois chopin.  agiovanni battista rubini.  agiovanni battista velluti.  ahistorical.  ahistory of music.  ahistory.  alive entertainment.  amaria felicia malibran.  amedical approach to music.  amusic and physical impacts.  amusic.  amusical expression.  amusical performers.  amusicians.  amusicological.  aopera.  apianistic health.  apianists.  apiano.  ascientific approach to music.  asigismond thalberg.  asingers.  atechniques of musical training.  avirtuosic musicians.  avocal health.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027939140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095800540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520958005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520958005/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY